  </div>

  <!-- METHODOLOGY & ASSUMPTIONS -->
  <h2>Methodology & Core Assumptions</h2>
  <p>To determine what Phillips 66 is actually worth, we use a <strong>Two-Stage Discounted Cash Flow (DCF)</strong> model. We project the free cash flow (FCF) the business will generate over the next 5 years (Phase 1), calculate a terminal value for all cash flows thereafter (Phase 2), and discount them back to today's dollars.</p>

  <p>Here are the exact inputs driving the math. No hidden adjustments.</p>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Base Year FCF ($M):</strong> ${baseFCF.toLocaleString()} (Our starting proxy for structural cash generation capability, based on the latest available Free Cash Flow).</li>
    <li><strong>Discount Rate (WACC):</strong> {(finalDiscountRate * 100).toFixed(1)}%. We derive this using a 10-Year Treasury yield of {(treasuryYield * 100).toFixed(2)}% as our risk-free rate, plus an equity risk premium adjusted for Phillips 66's beta. This is the hurdle rate representing the risk of the energy sector.</li>
    <li><strong>Growth Rate (Years 1-5):</strong> {(growthRatePhase1 * 100).toFixed(1)}%. We assume modest growth. Refining is cyclical and heavily dependent on crack spreads; midstream and chemicals provide stability, but rapid compounding is unlikely.</li>
    <li><strong>Terminal Growth Rate (Year 6+):</strong> {(growthRateTerminal * 100).toFixed(1)}%. We assume the business grows at roughly the rate of long-term inflation into perpetuity.</li>
    <li><strong>Shares Outstanding:</strong> {sharesOutstanding.toLocaleString()} million (Diluted).</li>
    <li><strong>Net Cash (Debt):</strong> ${netCash.toLocaleString()} million. Total cash minus total debt.</li>
  </ul>

  <!-- PROJECTIONS TABLE -->
  <h2>The Cash Flow Projections</h2>
  <p>Applying our {(growthRatePhase1 * 100).toFixed(1)}% growth rate to the base FCF, here is how the cash generation looks over the next five years, and what those future dollars are worth today.</p>

