        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </div>

  <!-- SENSITIVITY ANALYSIS -->
  <h2>Sensitivity Analysis</h2>
  <p>Our base case uses {(growthRatePhase1 * 100).toFixed(0)}% growth and {(finalDiscountRate * 100).toFixed(0)}% discount rate. Refining margins are notoriously hard to predict. Here is how the intrinsic value looks under different assumptions.</p>

  <div class="table-wrap">
    <table class="sensitivity-table">
      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th style="text-align:left">Discount Rate ↓ / Growth →</th>
          {sensitivityGrowth.map(g => (
            <th class={g === growthRatePhase1 ? 'current' : ''}>{(g * 100).toFixed(0)}%</th>
          ))}
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        {sensitivityTable.map(row => (
          <tr>
            <td>{(row.dr * 100).toFixed(0)}%</td>
            {row.values.map((v, i) => (
              <td class={row.dr === finalDiscountRate && sensitivityGrowth[i] === growthRatePhase1 ? 'current' : ''}>
                ${v}
              </td>
            ))}
          </tr>
        ))}
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </div>

  <!-- RISKS -->
  <h2>Risks & Variables</h2>
  <p>No model perfectly predicts reality. Here's what this DCF might miss:</p>

  <h3>Upside Risks</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Refining Margins (Crack Spreads):</strong> If global refining capacity remains tight or geopolitical events constrain supply, margins could remain structurally higher than our base case assumes.</li>
    <li><strong>Aggressive Buybacks:</strong> PSX generates significant cash and often returns it via buybacks. A rapidly shrinking share count increases the intrinsic value per remaining share.</li>
    <li><strong>Midstream/Chemicals Expansion:</strong> Successfully scaling these higher-margin, less volatile segments could warrant a lower discount rate (lower risk profile) and higher terminal value.</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Downside Risks</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Demand Destruction:</strong> An accelerated global transition to EVs or an economic recession could permanently depress demand for refined products.</li>
    <li><strong>Regulatory Pressures:</strong> Increased environmental regulations, carbon taxes, or changes to the Renewable Fuel Standard (RFS) obligations can significantly raise operating costs.</li>
    <li><strong>Commodity Volatility:</strong> The base FCF used in this model may represent a cyclical peak rather than a sustainable run rate. If margins revert heavily to the downside, the valuation collapses.</li>
  </ul>

  <!-- FAQ -->
  <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
  <div class="faq">
    <details>
      <summary>Why use Free Cash Flow instead of Earnings?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">Earnings (Net Income) include non-cash accounting adjustments (like depreciation) and ignore capital expenditures (CapEx). Free Cash Flow measures the actual cash left over after maintaining and expanding the business. In capital-intensive industries like refining, CapEx is massive, making FCF a much truer measure of value.</div>
    </details>
    <details>
      <summary>Where did you get the 10-Year Treasury rate?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">We utilize the current live (or recently updated) yield of the US 10-Year Treasury (4.18%). This serves as the "risk-free" foundation upon which we build the discount rate.</div>
    </details>
    <details>
      <summary>Is this a buy recommendation?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">No. This is purely a mathematical framework converting assumptions into a price. It is not investment advice. You must determine if you agree with the growth and risk assumptions before making any financial decision.</div>
    </details>
  </div>

